      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The economic argument for stricter immigration enforcement is that it would allow American workers to compete fairly in labor markets, as unregulated immigration drives down wages and increases competition for jobs. By reducing the supply of labor, stricter enforcement would put upward pressure on wages, particularly for low-skilled and low-wage workers, which would help to narrow the income gap and boost economic mobility for native-born Americans. Additionally, stricter enforcement would also help to reduce the strain on public resources, such as education and healthcare, by reducing the number of undocumented immigrants who rely on these systems.",
      "source": "target",
